{{italic title}} {{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Monet-ArgenteuilBasinWithASingleSailboat.jpg | image_size=270px | title=Argenteuil Basin with a Single Sailboat | other_language_1= | other_title_1= | artist=[[Claude Monet]] | year=1874 | medium=Oil on canvas | height_metric= 55 | width_metric= 65 | height_imperial= 21.6 | width_imperial= 25.6 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city= [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland]] | museum= [[National Gallery of Ireland]] }}
'''''Argenteuil Basin with a Single Sailboat''''' is an oil on canvas autumn scene of the basin at [[Argenteuil]], painted by French [[Impressionist]] artist [[Claude Monet]] in 1874.<ref name=NationalGallery>{{cite web |title=Argenteuil Basin with a Single Sailboat |publisher=National Gallery of Ireland |url=http://www.nationalgallery.ie/en/Learning/Schools/Impressionism/Works/Monet.aspx |accessdate= 18 January 2015}}</ref>
==Creation== The piece was created during Monet's residence at Argenteuil, a town on the banks of the [[Seine]], on the outskirts of [[Paris]]. Here Monet purchased a boat to be used as a floating studio and painted many scenes of the surrounding area.<ref name=NationalGallery/>
==National Gallery of Ireland== The painting was purchased by Irish playwright and activist [[Edward Martyn]] in 1899, on the advice of his cousin, [[George Moore (novelist)|George Moore]]. It was bequeathed to the National Gallery of Ireland in 1924.<ref name=eMuseum>{{cite web |title=eMuseum |publisher=National Gallery of Ireland |url=http://onlinecollection.nationalgallery.ie/view/objects/asitem/248/8/sortNumber-asc;jsessionid=4BCA839B5403A418978E44A004E02E20?t:state:flow=381a6dc7-ab82-4f53-a387-54626eb55ea1 |accessdate= 18 January 2015}}</ref> It is valued at €10m.<ref name=RteRestore>{{cite web |title=Restored Monet returned to National Gallery| publisher=[[Raidió Teilifís Éireann|RTÉ]]|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0701/627635-monet-national-gallery/ |date= 1 July 2014 |accessdate= 18 January 2015}}</ref>
===Vandalism and restoration=== At around 11am on 29 June 2012 a visitor to the gallery, Andrew Shannon, punched the painting causing "huge damage, shocking damage"<ref name=BelfastRestore>{{cite web |title=Vandalised Monet work restored| publisher=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/republic-of-ireland/vandalised-monet-work-restored-30397673.html |date= 1 July 2014 |accessdate= 18 January 2015}}</ref> with "an extensive three-branched tear".<ref name=NationalGalleryRestore>{{cite web |title=The Claude Monet Research & Conservation Project | publisher=National Gallery of Ireland|url=http://www.nationalgallery.ie/en/Learning/Schools/Impressionism/Conservation_Project.aspx |accessdate= 18 January 2015}}</ref>
After 18 months of restoration work, on 1 July 2014, the painting was re-hung in the gallery, behind protective glass.<ref name=RteRestore/> The restoration saw 7% of the damaged area being lost, in a process that involved sewing microscopic threads back together.<ref name=BelfastRestore/>
Shannon was jailed for 5 years for the attack.<ref name=MetroJailed>{{cite web |last=Wheaton |first=Oliver |title=Man is jailed for punching a hole through an £8 million Monet painting | publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|url=http://metro.co.uk/2014/12/06/man-is-jailed-for-punching-a-hole-through-an-8-million-monet-painting-4976300/ |date= 6 December 2014 |accessdate= 18 January 2015}}</ref>
