:{{redirect|Fahai|fictional monk in the Legend of the White Snake|Legend of the White Snake}} {{Infobox religious building | name = Fahai Temple | native_name = | image = Fahai Temple-the Hall of Mahavira.JPG | image_size = | alt = | caption =The Fahai Temple | map_type = | map_size = | map_alt = | map_caption = | location = [[Beijing]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|56|24.36|N|116|9|11.88|E|region:CN_type:landmark|display=title, inline}} | religious_affiliation = [[Buddhism]] | deity = | country = [[China]] | functional_status = | website = | founded_by = | year_completed = 1443 }}
[[Image:Shui-yue-guan-yin-Fa-hai-temple.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Water-moon Bodhisattva from the temple's Ming dynasty frescoes]]
The '''Fahai Temple''' ({{zh|c={{linktext|法|海|寺}}|p={{linktext|Fǎ|hǎi| Sì}}}}; {{lang|sa|धर्म समुद्र विहार}} ''{{IAST|Dharma Samudra Vihāra}}'') is [[Ming Dynasty]] [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] temple located at the foot of Cuiwei Mountain, about two kilometers to the north-east of Moshikou, [[Shijingshan District]], [[Beijing]], [[China]].
==History== Construction of the Fahai Temple started in 1439 during the [[Ming dynasty]] and was completed in 1443.
==Frescoes== The most distinguishing part of Fahai Temple is the Ming dynasty frescoes. The total area of the frescoes is 236.7 square meters. Comparing with other famous frescoes in China, such as the Yongle Palace frescoes and the [[Dunhuang]] frescoes, Fahai Temple's well-preserved frescoes are also notable in the depiction of figures, subtlety of patterns and the craft methods.
